<cell valign="middle" halign ="center"><m>2.303</m></cell>
<cell valign="middle" halign ="center"><m>4.605</m></cell>
</row>
</tabular>
</table>
<figure xml:id="CNX_Calc_Figure_04_06_022">
<image source="CNX_Calc_Figure_04_06_014.jpg" width="50%">
<description>"The function f(x) = ln(x) is graphed."  </description></image> <caption>The natural logarithm function approaches <m>\infty</m> as <m>x\to\infty.</m></caption>
</figure>
<example xml:id="fs-id1165042469818">
<title>Determining End Behavior for a Transcendental Function</title>
 <statement id="fs-id1165042469822">
<p id="fs-id1165042469828">Find the limits as <m>x\to\infty</m> and <m>x\to-\infty</m> for <m>f(x)=\frac{(2+3e^x)}{(7-5e^x)}</m> and describe the end behavior of <m>f.</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165042711622">
<p id="fs-id1165042711624">To find the limit as <m>x\to\infty,</m> divide the numerator and denominator by <m>e^x\text{ : }</m></p>
<md><mrow>\limit_{x\to\infty}f(x)\amp =\limit_{x\to\infty}\frac{2+3e^x}{7-5e^x}</mrow><mrow>=\limit_{x\to\infty}\frac{(2/e^x)+3}{(7/e^x)-5}.</mrow></md>
<p id="fs-id1165042499478">As shown in <xref ref="CNX_Calc_Figure_04_06_021"/>, <m>e^x\to\infty</m> as <m>x\to\infty.</m> Therefore,</p>
<me>\limit_{x\to\infty}\frac{2}{e^x}=0=\limit_{x\to\infty}\frac{7}{e^x}.</me>
<p id="fs-id1165042499577">We conclude that <m>\limit_{x\to\infty}f(x)=-\frac{3}{5},</m> and the graph of <m>f</m> approaches the horizontal asymptote <m>y=-\frac{3}{5}</m> as <m>x\to\infty.</m> To find the limit as <m>x\to-\infty,</m> use the fact that <m>e^x\to0</m> as <m>x\to-\infty</m> to conclude that <m>\limit_{x\to\infty}f(x)=\frac{2}{7},</m> and therefore the graph of approaches the horizontal asymptote <m>y=\frac{2}{7}</m> as <m>x\to-\infty.</m></p>
</solution>
</example>
<exercise><statement id="fs-id1165042711312">
<p id="fs-id1165042711314">Find the limits as <m>x\to\infty</m> and <m>x\to-\infty</m> for <m>f(x)=\frac{(3e^x-4)}{(5e^x+2)}.</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165042711399">
<p id="fs-id1165042711402"><m>\limit_{x\to\infty}f(x)=\frac{3}{5},</m> <m>\limit_{x\to-\infty}f(x)=-2</m></p>
</solution>
<hint>
<p id="fs-id1165042711480"><m>\limit_{x\to\infty}e^x=\infty</m> and <m>\limit_{x\to\infty}e^x=0.</m></p>
</hint></exercise>
</subsection> -->


<!-- <subsection id="fs-id1165042633662" class="key-concepts">
<title>Key Concepts</title>
<ul>
<li>The limit of <m>f(x)</m> is <m>L</m> as <m>x\to\infty</m> (or as <m>x\to-\infty)</m> if the values <m>f(x)</m> become arbitrarily close to <m>L</m> as <m>x</m> becomes sufficiently large.</li>
<li>The limit of <m>f(x)</m> is <m>\infty</m> as <m>x\to\infty</m> if <m>f(x)</m> becomes arbitrarily large as <m>x</m> becomes sufficiently large. The limit of <m>f(x)</m> is <m>-\infty</m> as <m>x\to\infty</m> if <m>f(x)\lt 0</m> and <m>|f(x)|</m> becomes arbitrarily large as <m>x</m> becomes sufficiently large. We can define the limit of <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>-\infty</m> similarly.</li>
<li>For a polynomial function <m>p(x)=a_nx^n+a_{n-1} x^{n-1} +\dots+a_1x+a_0,</m> where <m>a_n\neq 0,</m> the end behavior is determined by the leading term <m>a_nx^n.</m> If <m>n\neq 0,</m> <m>p(x)</m> approaches <m>\infty</m> or <m>-\infty</m> at each end.</li>
<li>For a rational function <m>f(x)=\frac{p(x)}{q(x)},</m> the end behavior is determined by the relationship between the degree of <m>p</m> and the degree of <m>q.</m> If the degree of <m>p</m> is less than the degree of <m>q,</m> the line <m>y=0</m> is a horizontal asymptote for <m>f.</m> If the degree of <m>p</m> is equal to the degree of <m>q,</m> then the line <m>y=\frac{a_n}{b_n}</m> is a horizontal asymptote, where <m>a_n</m> and <m>b_n</m> are the leading coefficients of <m>p</m> and <m>q,</m> respectively. If the degree of <m>p</m> is greater than the degree of <m>q,</m> then <m>f</m> approaches <m>\infty</m> or <m>-\infty</m> at each end.</li>
</ul>
</subsection> -->
</section>
<?ignore
<section id="fs-id1165042640624" class="section-exercises">
<p id="fs-id1165042640628">For the following exercises, examine the graphs. Identify where the vertical asymptotes are located.</p>

<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165042640635">
<description>"The function graphed decreases very rapidly as it approaches x = 1 from the left, and on the other side of x = 1, it seems to start near infinity and then decrease rapidly.">
<image source="CNX_Calc_Figure_04_06_201.jpg" width="50%">

</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165042640651">
<p id="fs-id1165042640653"><m>x=1</m></p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165042640668">
<description>"The function graphed increases very rapidly as it approaches x = &#x2212;3 from the left, and on the other side of x = &#x2212;3, it seems to start near negative infinity and then increase rapidly to form a sort of U shape that is pointing down, with the other side of the U being at x = 2. On the other side of x = 2, the graph seems to start near infinity and then decrease rapidly.">
<image source="CNX_Calc_Figure_04_06_202.jpg" width="50%">

</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043197222">
<description>"The function graphed decreases very rapidly as it approaches x = &#x2212;1 from the left, and on the other side of x = &#x2212;1, it seems to start near negative infinity and then increase rapidly to form a sort of U shape that is pointing down, with the other side of the U being at x = 2. On the other side of x = 2, the graph seems to start near infinity and then decrease rapidly.">
<image source="CNX_Calc_Figure_04_06_203.jpg" width="50%">

</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165043197241">
<p id="fs-id1165043197243"><m>x=-1,x=2</m></p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043197267">
<description>"The function graphed decreases very rapidly as it approaches x = 0 from the left, and on the other side of x = 0, it seems to start near infinity and then decrease rapidly to form a sort of U shape that is pointing up, with the other side of the U being at x = 1. On the other side of x = 1, there is another U shape pointing down, with its other side being at x = 2. On the other side of x = 2, the graph seems to start near negative infinity and then increase rapidly.">
<image source="CNX_Calc_Figure_04_06_204.jpg" width="50%">

</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043197320">
<description>"The function graphed decreases very rapidly as it approaches x = 0 from the left, and on the other side of x = 0, it seems to start near infinity and then decrease rapidly to form a sort of U shape that is pointing up, with the other side being a normal function that appears as if it will take the entirety of the values of the x-axis.">
<image source="CNX_Calc_Figure_04_06_205.jpg" width="50%">

</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165043197338">
<p id="fs-id1165043197340"><m>x=0</m></p>
</solution>

<p id="fs-id1165043197353">For the following functions <m>f(x),</m> determine whether there is an asymptote at <m>x=a.</m> Justify your answer without graphing on a calculator.</p>

<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043197385">
<p id="fs-id1165043197388"><m>f(x)=\frac{x+1}{x^2+5x+4},a=-1</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043197449">
<p id="fs-id1165043197451"><m>f(x)=\frac{xx-2},a=2</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165043197487">
<p id="fs-id1165043197490">Yes, there is a vertical asymptote</p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043197497">
<p id="fs-id1165043197500"><m>f(x)=<m:msup>(x+2)}{3/2</m:msup>,a=-2</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043197557">
<p id="fs-id1165043197560"><m>f(x)=(x-1)^{-1/3},a=1</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165043197608">
<p id="fs-id1165043197610">Yes, there is vertical asymptote</p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043197618">
<p id="fs-id1165043197620"><m>f(x)=1+<m:msup>x-2/5</m:msup>,a=1</m></p>
</statement>

<p id="fs-id1165043377731">For the following exercises, evaluate the limit.</p>

<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043377736">
<p id="fs-id1165043377738"><m>\limit_{x\to\infty}\frac{13x+6}</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165043377770">
<p id="fs-id1165043377772"><m>0</m></p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043377782">
<p id="fs-id1165043377784"><m>\limit_{x\to\infty}\frac{2x-5}{4x}</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043377835">
<p id="fs-id1165043377837"><m>\limit_{x\to\infty}\frac{x^2-2x+5}{x+2}</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165043377882">
<p id="fs-id1165043377884"><m>\infty</m></p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043377893">
<p id="fs-id1165043377896"><m>\limit_{x\to-\infty}\frac{3x^3-2x}{x^2+2x+8}</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043377965">
<p id="fs-id1165043377967"><m>\limit_{x\to-\infty}\frac{x^4-4x^3+1}{2-2x^2-7x^4}</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165043378032">
<p id="fs-id1165043378034"><m>-\frac{1}{7}</m></p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043378050">
<p id="fs-id1165043378052"><m>\limit_{x\to\infty}\frac{3}{x}{\sqrt{x^2+1}}</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043216345">
<p id="fs-id1165043216347"><m>\limit_{x\to-\infty}\frac{\sqrt{4x^2-1}}{x+2}</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165043216392">
<p id="fs-id1165043216394"><m>-2</m></p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043216404">
<p id="fs-id1165043216407"><m>\limit_{x\to\infty}\frac{4}{x}{\sqrt{x^2-1}}</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043216457">
<p id="fs-id1165043216459"><m>\limit_{x\to-\infty}\frac{4}{x}{\sqrt{x^2-1}}</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165043216499">
<p id="fs-id1165043216501"><m>-4</m></p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043216512">
<p id="fs-id1165043216514"><m>\limit_{x\to\infty}\frac{2\sqrt{x}}{x-\sqrt{x}+1}</m></p>
</statement>

<p id="fs-id1165043216563">For the following exercises, find the horizontal and vertical asymptotes.</p>

<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043216569">
<p id="fs-id1165043216571"><m>f(x)=x-\frac{9}{x}</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165043216597">
<p id="fs-id1165043216600">Horizontal: none, vertical: <m>x=0</m></p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043216616">
<p id="fs-id1165043216618"><m>f(x)=\frac{11-x^2}</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043216681">
<p id="fs-id1165043216683"><m>f(x)=\frac{x^3}{4-x^2}</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165043216718">
<p id="fs-id1165043216720">Horizontal: none, vertical: <m>x=\pm2</m></p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043216739">
<p id="fs-id1165043216741"><m>f(x)=\frac{x^2+3}{x^2+1}</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043210296">
<p id="fs-id1165043210298"><m>f(x)=\sin(x) \sin(2x)</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165043210338">
<p id="fs-id1165043210340">Horizontal: none, vertical: none</p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043210348">
<p id="fs-id1165043210350"><m>f(x)=\text{ cos } x+\text{ cos }(3x)+\text{ cos }(5x)</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043210411">
<p id="fs-id1165043210413"><m>f(x)=\frac{x \sin(x)}{x^2-1}</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165043210455">
<p id="fs-id1165043210457">Horizontal: <m>y=0,</m> vertical: <m>x=\pm1</m></p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043210487">
<p id="fs-id1165043210489"><m>f(x)=\frac{x\sin(x)}</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043210552">
<p id="fs-id1165043210554"><m>f(x)=\frac{1x^3+x^2}</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165043210589">
<p id="fs-id1165043210591">Horizontal: <m>y=0,</m> vertical: <m>x=0</m> and <m>x=-1</m></p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043210628">
<p id="fs-id1165043210630"><m>f(x)=\frac{1x-1}-2x</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043349200">
<p id="fs-id1165043349202"><m>f(x)=\frac{x^3+1}{x^3-1}</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165043349242">
<p id="fs-id1165043349244">Horizontal: <m>y=1,</m> vertical: <m>x=1</m></p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043349272">
<p id="fs-id1165043349274"><m>f(x)=\frac{\sin x+\text{ cos } x}{\sin x-\text{ cos } x}</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043349348">
<p id="fs-id1165043349350"><m>f(x)=x-\sin x</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165043349375">
<p id="fs-id1165043349378">Horizontal: none, vertical: none</p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043349385">
<p id="fs-id1165043349388"><m>f(x)=\frac{1}{x}-\sqrt{x}</m></p>
</statement>

<p id="fs-id1165043349432">For the following exercises, construct a function <m>f(x)</m> that has the given asymptotes.</p>

<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043349450">
<p id="fs-id1165043349452"><m>x=1</m> and <m>y=2</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165043349474">
<p id="fs-id1165043349476">Answers will vary, for example: <m>y=\frac{2}{x}{x-1}</m></p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043349504">
<p id="fs-id1165043349506"><m>x=1</m> and <m>y=0</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043349561">
<p id="fs-id1165043349563"><m>y=4,</m> <m>x=-1</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165043349587">
<p id="fs-id1165043349589">Answers will vary, for example: <m>y=\frac{4}{x}{x+1}</m></p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043349617">
<p id="fs-id1165043349619"><m>x=0</m></p>
</statement>

<p id="fs-id1165042709113">For the following exercises, graph the function on a graphing calculator on the window <m>x=[-5,5]</m> and estimate the horizontal asymptote or limit. Then, calculate the actual horizontal asymptote or limit.</p>

<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165042709140">
<p id="fs-id1165042709142"><emphasis effect="bold">[T]</emphasis> <m>f(x)=\frac{1x+10}</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165042709175">
<p id="fs-id1165042709177"><m>y=0</m></p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165042709192">
<p id="fs-id1165042709194"><emphasis effect="bold">[T]</emphasis> <m>f(x)=\frac{x+1}{x^2+7x+6}</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165042709259">
<p id="fs-id1165042709261"><emphasis effect="bold">[T]</emphasis> <m>\limit_{x\to-\infty}x^2+10x+25</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165042709304">
<p id="fs-id1165042709306"><m>\infty</m></p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165042709316">
<p id="fs-id1165042709318"><emphasis effect="bold">[T]</emphasis> <m>\limit_{x\to-\infty}\frac{x+2}{x^2+7x+6}</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165042709387">
<p id="fs-id1165042709389"><emphasis effect="bold">[T]</emphasis> <m>\limit_{x\to\infty}\frac{3x+2}{x+5}</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165042709431">
<p id="fs-id1165042709433"><m>y=3</m></p>
</solution>

<p id="fs-id1165042709446">For the following exercises, draw a graph of the functions without using a calculator. Be sure to notice all important features of the graph: local maxima and minima, inflection points, and asymptotic behavior.</p>

<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165042709453">
<p id="fs-id1165042709456"><m>y=3x^2+2x+4</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165042709504">
<p id="fs-id1165042709506"><m>y=x^3-3x^2+4</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165042558119"><p id="fs-id1165042558120">
<description>"The function starts in the third quadrant, increases to pass through (&#x2212;1, 0), increases to a maximum and y intercept at 4, decreases to touch (2, 0), and then increases to (4, 20).">
<image source="CNX_Calc_Figure_04_06_207.jpg" width="50%">
</p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165042558142">
<p id="fs-id1165042558144"><m>y=\frac{2x+1}{x^2+6x+5}</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165042558207">
<p id="fs-id1165042558209"><m>y=\frac{x^3+4x^2+3x}{3x+9}</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165042558252"><p id="fs-id1165042558253">
<description>"An upward-facing parabola with minimum between x = 0 and x = &#x2212;1 with y intercept between 0 and 1.">
<image source="CNX_Calc_Figure_04_06_209.jpg" width="50%">
</p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165042558274">
<p id="fs-id1165042558276"><m>y=\frac{x^2+x-2}{x^2-3x-4}</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165042558345">
<p id="fs-id1165042558347"><m>y=\sqrt{x^2-5x+4}</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165042558375"><p id="fs-id1165042558376">
<description>"This graph starts at (&#x2212;2, 4) and decreases in a convex way to (1, 0). Then the graph starts again at (4, 0) and increases in a convex way to (6, 3).">
<image source="CNX_Calc_Figure_04_06_211.jpg" width="50%">
</p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165042558397">
<p id="fs-id1165042558399"><m>y=2x\sqrt{16-x^2}</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165042558448">
<p id="fs-id1165042558450"><m>y=\frac{\text{ cos } xx},</m> on <m>x=[-2\pi,2\pi]</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165042558495"><p id="fs-id1165042558496">
<description>"This graph has vertical asymptote at x = 0. The first part of the function occurs in the second and third quadrants and starts in the third quadrant just below (&#x2212;2&#x3C0;, 0), increases and passes through the x axis at &#x2212;3&#x3C0;/2, reaches a maximum and then decreases through the x axis at &#x2212;&#x3C0;/2 before approaching the asymptote. On the other side of the asymptote, the function starts in the first quadrant, decreases quickly to pass through &#x3C0;/2, decreases to a local minimum and then increases through (3&#x3C0;/2, 0) before staying just above (2&#x3C0;, 0).">
<image source="CNX_Calc_Figure_04_06_213.jpg" width="50%">
</p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165042558521">
<p id="fs-id1165042558523"><m>y=e^x-x^3</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043404026">
<p id="fs-id1165043404029"><m>y=x \tan  x,x=[-\pi,\pi]</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165043404066"><p id="fs-id1165043404067">
<description>"This graph has vertical asymptotes at x = &#xB1;&#x3C0;/2. The graph is symmetric about the y axis, so describing the left hand side will be sufficient. The function starts at (&#x2212;&#x3C0;, 0) and decreases quickly to the asymptote. Then it starts on the other side of the asymptote in the second quadrant and decreases to the the origin.">
<image source="CNX_Calc_Figure_04_06_215.jpg" width="50%">
</p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043404090">
<p id="fs-id1165043404092"><m>y=x \text{ ln }(x),x\gt 0</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043404143">
<p id="fs-id1165043404145"><m>y=x^2\sin(x),x=[-2\pi,2\pi]</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165043404193"><p id="fs-id1165043404194">
<description>"This function starts at (&#x2212;2&#x3C0;, 0), increases to near (&#x2212;3&#x3C0;/2, 25), decreases through (&#x2212;&#x3C0;, 0), achieves a local minimum and then increases through the origin. On the other side of the origin, the graph is the same but flipped, that is, it is congruent to the other half by a rotation of 180 degrees.">
<image source="CNX_Calc_Figure_04_06_217.jpg" width="50%">
</p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043404217">
<p id="fs-id1165043404219">For <m>f(x)=\frac{P(x)}{Q(x)}</m> to have an asymptote at <m>y=2</m> then the polynomials <m>P(x)</m> and <m>Q(x)</m> must have what relation?</p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043404363">
<p id="fs-id1165043404366">For <m>f(x)=\frac{P(x)}{Q(x)}</m> to have an asymptote at <m>x=0,</m> then the polynomials <m>P(x)</m> and <m>Q(x).</m> must have what relation?</p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165043208541">
<p xml:id="fs-id1165043208543">The degree of <m>Q(x)</m> must be greater than the degree of <m>P(x)</m>.</p></solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043208600">
<p id="fs-id1165043208602">If <m>f'(x)</m> has asymptotes at <m>y=3</m> and <m>x=1,</m> then <m>f(x)</m> has what asymptotes?</p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043208678">
<p id="fs-id1165043208681">Both <m>f(x)=\frac{1(x-1)}</m> and <m>g(x)=\frac{1(x-1)^2}</m> have asymptotes at <m>x=1</m> and <m>y=0.</m> What is the most obvious difference between these two functions?</p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1165043208775">
<p xml:id="fs-id1165043208777"><m>\limit_{x\to1^-}f(x)=-\infty \text{ and } \limit_{x\to1^-}g(x)=\infty</m></p></solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1165043208847">
<p id="fs-id1165043208849">True or false: Every ratio of polynomials has vertical asymptotes.</p>
</statement>

</section>
</content>
<glossary>
<definition id="fs-id1165043208865">
<term>end behavior</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1165043208870">the behavior of a function as <m>x\to\infty</m> and <m>x\to-\infty</m></meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1165043208899">
<term>horizontal asymptote</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1165043208905">if <m>\limit_{x\to\infty}f(x)=L</m> or <m>\limit_{x\to-\infty}f(x)=L,</m> then <m>y=L</m> is a horizontal asymptote of <m>f</m></meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1165042462524">
<term>infinite limit at infinity</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1165042462530">a function that becomes arbitrarily large as <m>x</m> becomes large</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1165042462539">
<term>limit at infinity</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1165042462545">the limiting value, if it exists, of a function as <m>x\to\infty</m> or <m>x\to-\infty</m></meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1165042462574">
<term>oblique asymptote</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1165042462579">the line <m>y=mx+b</m> if <m>f(x)</m> approaches it as <m>x\to\infty</m> or <m>x\to-\infty</m></meaning>
</definition>
</glossary>
</document>
?>
